import sqlite3 # Once imported in a single notebook, it is available to us throughout the rest of the notebook. 
# connect to database, if not there, create it.
connectionToDatabase = sqlite3.connect('CurlingLeague') 

cursor = connectionToDatabase.cursor()
cursor.execute('''drop table IF EXISTS Team''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()

cursor.execute('''create table Team (TeamID text PRIMARY KEY, LeagueStanding int, NumberWins int, NumberLosses int, AvgScore real, LeagueID text)''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()

cursor = connectionToDatabase.cursor()
cursor.execute('''drop table IF EXISTS Players''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()

cursor.execute('''create table Players (PlayerID text PRIMARY KEY, Name text, TeamID text, DomesticScore real, International Score real, Stadium ID text)''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()

cursor.execute('''drop table IF EXISTS League''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()

cursor.execute('''create table League (LeagueID text PRIMARY KEY, NumberParticipants int, StartDate text, EndDate text)''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()

cursor.execute('''drop table IF EXISTS MatchLocations''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()

cursor.execute('''create table MatchLocations (StadiumID text PRIMARY KEY, Country text, IndoorOutdoor text, City text)''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()

cursor.execute('''drop table IF EXISTS Matches''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()

cursor.execute('''create table Matches (MatchID text PRIMARY KEY, TeamID text, StadiumID text, MatchResult text)''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()

cursor.execute('''insert into Team values ('01', '2', '0', '3', '4', '001');''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()
cursor.execute('''insert into Team values ('02', '1', '3', '0', '5.1', '001');''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()
cursor.execute('''insert into Players values ('1234', 'Jeff Johnson', '01', '5', '3', '9024');''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()
cursor.execute('''insert into MatchLocations values ('9024', 'United States', 'Outdoor', 'Los Angeles' );''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()
cursor.execute('''insert into League values ('001', '2', '1/1/19', '5/1/19');''')
connectionToDatabase.commit()

We did need to refine our ER diagram in order to successfully input the data. For example, we had to remove the attribute "Current Game" from matches. Several adjustments of this nature were made, and we put our new ER diagram at the top of this notebook.
Although the curling database would require lots of data to carry out effective queries, here are three questions we could answer with queries:
Question: Who are the players that have a domestic score above 3?

This question is important because the fantasy players must draft players onto their teams. Given that curling competitors can travel all around the world for their matches, it is crucial for the drafting team to balance their roster with strong performers at both their home stadiums and abroad. Our query worked as expected, and with hundreds of players in the database, would be incredibly useful in the drafting process.
Question: List the rankings of all the teams in the league, displaying just the Team ID.

This query would allow players to view the current standings after a certain amount of games. Its also important to note that in viewing rankings, we dont care about all of the data that could be displayedwe want to limit our output to just indicate which teams are ranked the highest. The query also worked as expected, although it would be made better with actual team names instead of team IDs.
Question: Do any players have first names starting with J? If so, list their stats.

This question allows us to conceptualize a basic search feature. Basically, the user could interact with the database management system and search for a familiar player that they dont remember the full name of. The database can return the name of the person and all of their statistics by just indicating the letter J, which is exactly the result we saw in the query (this feature will be more useful when more data is entered).
